There seems to be a problem with the type inference 
(used for content assistance)
in conjunction with object members assigned to variables 
(or other object members).

The content assistance works fine for all examples given in
the snippet below, except for the expression
"this.s.a" in function "foo2".

The inference engine seems to e able to "follow"
assignments (via ":" in object lieterals) of "simple"
variables to object members. (See the use of "t" in "foo3".)

However it does not seem to be able to "follow"
assignments of members of objects to object members
as shown in "foo2". 
In this case "x.x1" is assigned to "s". The type of "s"
seems to be unknown. Consequently the jsdt content assist does not
make any suggestions. 


var x = {
    x1 : {
        a : "a",
        b : "b"
    }
};

x.x1; // okay

var y = x;

y.x1;   // okay
y.x1.a; // okay
y.x1.b; // okay

var z = x.x1;
z.a;          // okay
z.b;          // okay

var l = {
    r : x,
    foo1 : function() {
        this.r.x1; // okay
    },
    s : x.x1, // okay

    foo2 : function() {
        /**
         * does not work
         * i.e. typing "this.s. Control-Space" does
         * not make any proposals
         */
        this.s.a;
    },

    t : {
        u : {
            m : 3
        }
    },
    foo3 : function() {
        this.t;      // okay
        this.t.u;    // okay
        this.t.u.m;  // okay
    }
};

This behaviour has been observed with the version below:

JavaScript Developer Tools
Version: 1.1.2.v200908101420-77-FGCCcNBC-BhLcE_Pm
Build id: 20090917225226

Build Identifier: 20090920-1017

It is perfectly valid in a class method to refer to class fields defined later.
Like this:
class Test{
public:
  void testMethod()
  {
    myField=1;
  }
protected:
  int myField;
};

Eclipse highlight this as valid code, 'go to definition' works ok, but
code assistant fails to propose names of this fields in methods
prior to definition of this fields. 
In example above 'myField' won't be proposed in a testMethod.


Reproducible: Always

Steps to Reproduce:
1. Paste following snippet:
class Test{
public:
  void testMethod()
  {
  }
protected:
  int myField;
};
2. Place cursor inside testMethod.
3. Type my and  invoke any completion except for 'word completion'. 'myField' is not proposed.

I20100112-0800.

The deprecation warning for a type should not include the package name.

Test Case:
1. paste the following snippet into the Package Explorer.

package a.b.c.d;

/** @deprecated */
public class Deprecated {

}
package a.b.c.d;

public class T {

	a.b.c.d.Deprecated f;

}

==> the deprecation warning covers "a.b.c.d.Deprecated" but should only cover the type name ("Deprecated") since the package itself is not deprecated. This is similar to deprecated methods where we also only mark the method as deprecated.

See also bug 169995.

