Currently the TAF does not support annotation attributes of primitive type (and String) with * multiplicity. To see that this is not supported checkout the following project from Eclipse Tigerstripce CVS:

org.eclipse.tigerstripe/plugins/org.eclipse.tigerstripe.annotation.example.person

Within the ecore Person model the attributes emails and phones are both of type String with * multiplicity. Neither of these attributes are editable when the annotation has been applied to a IResource.

From the look of the code it seems this has not been implemented yet as the class org.eclipse.tigerstripe.annotation.ui.core.properties.StringListProperty contains the following:

protected CellEditor createEditor(Composite parent) {
		return null;//return CellEditorFactory.createDialogCellEditor(parent, feature, (List<String>)getValue());
	}

There is an EFS provider that connects remotely and prompts a user for a password on connect.  When a user attempts to open a project that uses this EFS provider, the following code in FileSystemResourceManager.read() gets invoked:

...
try {
-->	in = new BufferedInputStream(descriptionStore.openInputStream(EFS.NONE, null));
	description = new ProjectDescriptionReader(target).read(new InputSource(in));
} catch (CoreException e) {
	//try the legacy location in the meta area
	description = getWorkspace().getMetaArea().readOldDescription(target);
	if (description != null)
		return description;
-->	if (!descriptionStore.fetchInfo().exists()) {
		String msg = NLS.bind(Messages.resources_missingProjectMeta, target.getName());
		throw new ResourceException(IResourceStatus.FAILED_READ_METADATA, target.getFullPath(), msg, null);
...

The openInputStream() call causes a connect call from the EFS provider that prompts for a password.  If the user clicks cancel on the password prompt, the EFS provider throws an exception indicating that the operation is cancelled.  FileSystemResourceManager.read() catches the exception and then ends up calling descriptionStore.fetchInfo().  But that is another call to the same EFS provider, and since and EFS provider is stateless, it ends up having to prompt for the password again even though the user already cancelled the operation earlier.

I'm not sure how to resolve this problem but perhaps a check of the exception can be used to determine whether to query the descriptionStore or not.

How about a fairy tale (or a "green thread" :-)) describing the life of a new E4 developer:
=== Say I am a developer who just picked up E4 to make my new RCP text editor. I've scanned a whitepaper that explained that E4 uses model, and, in particluar the MEditor interface to represent an editor.
That sounds cool so I make my MEditor class, and... hmm... I guess I need to create some SWT controls to show up the contents? StyledText? OK, that needs parent composite... Hmm... Where do I get the parent composite? And... hmm... where do I place the code that actually creates the conrol? ===
At this point the story supposed to somehow jump to adding lines like this:
@Inject private Composite parent;
to the editor's class for the parent composite and add
@PostConstruct void init() {...}
to hold the code to create the control.
=== Question is: how would the developer know about this?
(The example is intentionally oversimplified. Those two values probably can be considered "well known" things and we can say that we'll have a wizard that would create a sceleton editor with those lines. But the point here is that we need to consider a general solution to this.)

setFocus() should look something like this:

bc. 
   @Override
   public void setFocus() {
       UIThreadRunnable.syncExec(new VoidResult() {
            public void run() {
               IEditorPart editor = partReference.getEditor(false);
               if (editor != null) {
                  editor.setFocus();
               }
            }
       });
   }

Note the following JUnit test:
    public void testSettingDetachedObject() {
        EntityManager em = createEntityManager();
        List<Address> results = (List<Address>) em.createQuery("Select a from Address a").getResultList();
        Department dept1 = new Department("Dept1");
        Department dept2 = new Department("Dept2");
        beginTransaction(em);
        em.persist(dept1);
        em.persist(dept2);
        commitTransaction(em);
        em.clear();

        Employee emp = new Employee("Bob", "Bob");
        beginTransaction(em);
        em.persist(emp);
        emp.setDepartment(dept1);
        em.flush();
        emp.setDepartment(dept2); //<-- only the UOW is checked for existence
        commitTransaction(em); //<-- fails here
    }

When the Change Tracker event occurs EclipseLink uses UOW.isNewObject() to determine if the referenced object is new.  However this check assumes discoverAllUnregisteredNewObjects() has been called and in the case of Change Tracking that method is not called.

The solution here is to alter the path Change Tracking uses so that the detached is recognized as such or appropriate exceptions are thrown in the case of CascadeType.PERSIST

Build Identifier: 20090920-1017

The UserDataService class creates eventConsumerJob that, by default, is running while running Eclipse.
JBT PDE tests have to wait until all Eclipse jobs are finished (Eclipse builder, validators ...). The following method is used:

public static void waitForIdle(long delay) {
	long start = System.currentTimeMillis();

	while (!Job.getJobManager().isIdle()) {
		delay(delay);
		if ( (System.currentTimeMillis()-start) > MAX_IDLE ) 
			throw new RuntimeException("A long running task detected"); //$NON-NLS-1$
	}
}

Since eventConsumerJob is never finished, this method throws RuntimeException after MAX_IDLE seconds.
It is not possible to stop monitoring without introducing a dependency to the org.eclipse.epp.usagedata.gathering plugin.

I see two solutions to solve the problem :

- creating eventConsumerJob so that it is started and finished periodically 
- the UsageDataCaptureActivator.start method would check for a system property (org.eclipse.epp.usagedata.gathering.disabled, for instance); if the property is true, the monitoring wouldn't be started. The tests could be started with the VM args -Dorg.eclipse.epp.usagedata.gathering.disabled=true
This solution is easier to implement.

A similar problem was existing in mylyn (https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=198241)

Reproducible: Always

Steps to Reproduce:
Job.getJobManager().isIdle() always returns false if org.eclipse.epp.usagedata.gathering is started.

Build Identifier: 20090920-1017

When you want to call virtual method of a base class, overridden in current class, you need to explicitly specify class name before method name.
Base::method();
In example below method of base class is not proposed.

class A{
public:
  virtual void test()
  {
  }
};
class B:public A{
public:
  void test()
  {
  }
  void func()
  {
    A::t|
  }
};

If you place cursor at position of | and invoke completion, only keywords that are starting with 't' are proposed.


Reproducible: Always

