- enable Java > Editor > Content Assist > Completion overwrites
- set caret after 's.e'
- Ctrl+Space

a) type 'n' and move caret back by one char (back to after 's.e'), hit 'Enter'
===> the whole word after 'e' is highlighted and replaced by the selected proposal as expected.

b) instead of (a) type 'q' and move caret back by one char (back to after 's.e'), hit 'Enter'
===> one char from the end is left out. Each time this is repeated one char from the end of the word is left out from highlighting and when you hit 'Enter', the characters at the end are not replaced.

After typing 'q' and moving back the caret 2 times and then hitting 'Enter' on endsWith(..) proposal we see : 
       s.endsWithth(s);

==> Expected: All the characters are highlighted and replaced on selecting a proposal from the list.
       s.endsWith(s);

This scenario seems to occur whenever a proposal gets added at the top of list as a result of moving back the caret. It does not occur when 'n' is typed in the example, since the 2 extra proposals(equals*(..) ) get added at the bottom whereas when 'q' is typed, endsWith(..) gets added at the top of the list. Another example where this happens:
void m() {
       s.chaAt(0); 

}
If you type 'h' and move the caret, works fine but if you type 'o' and move caret back chars are left out from highlighting from the end.

